        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We select a bandwidth of 1875 MHz, which corresponds to a resolution of 65 km/s at the frequency of the observed CO(2-1) line. As the expected line width is much broader, this resolution is sufficient to spectrally resolve this line.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In order to constrain the quenching mechanism, it is crucial to know the distribution of the molecular gas compared to the stellar light. This is in particular important when the CO emission is higher than expected based on the SFR, in which case the S/N is also significantly higher.

The rest-frame optical effective radius of the galaxy 1.67 kpc. At a redshift of z=0.604, this radius corresponds to 0.25 arcsec. We select a resolution of 0.3 arcsec, corresponding to the C36-5 configuration in band 4. Using this resolution, we can assess whether the CO emission is more concentrated, similarly distributed, or less concentrated than the stellar light. Using the C36-4 configuration (with a resolution of 0.5), we can not assess whether the CO emission is more concentrated than the stellar light, while the C36-6 (with a resolution of 0.2) configuration would lead to a larger integration time for the same S/N.

The largest angular scale, which corresponds to 12 times the effective radius, is set to detect CO in case it is significantly offset from the stellar light.

The C36-5 configuration is scheduled for 2016 May 31, to observe hour angles ~10hr-02hr. Our target has an RA of 10hr and thus falls in this range.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We calculate the S/N value of the CO(2-1) line based on the best-fit SFR measurement and assuming that the galaxy falls onto the star formation surface density - molecular gas surface density relation for low-redshift galaxies. For a SFR of 2.5 Msol/yr, a redshift of z=0.604, and a velocity dispersion of 220 km/s, we find a velocity integrated flux of 210 mJy km/s and a peak line flux density of 380 uJy, as explained in the immediate objective section of the proposal. In this calculation we assume a CO to H_2 conversion (alpha_CO) of 4.36 and a luminosity ratio CO(2-1)/CO(1-0) of 1, as motivated in the proposal. For a bandwidth of 515 km/s, which is the expected FWHM of the CO emission line, we need a S/N &gt; 6 in order to robustly identify the CO line. This S/N limit requires a sensitivity of 63 microJansky. 

This calculation may represent a conservative scenario: in case our target follows the trend of local post-starburst galaxies, we will find a larger molecular gas content, and thus a higher S/N measurement for CO(2-1).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
