    <prp:abstract>Out to a redshift of z~1, the massive end of the galaxy population is dominated by elliptical galaxies with quiescent stellar populations. Despite many investigations, the question of why these galaxies stopped forming stars remains subject to much debate. We propose to constrain the physical processes responsible for the suppression of star formation by observing the molecular gas content in a recently quenched post-starburst galaxy at z=0.604. The stellar light of this galaxy is dominated by A-type stars, and thus it likely just experienced its initial quenching phase. Using the molecular gas content and its spatial distribution, in combination with star formation properties from UV-IR data and hydrodynamic galaxy formation simulations, this study will provide new insights into why galaxies enter their quiescent phase. This study is a pilot program and will pave the way for ALMA studies of larger and/or more distant post-starburst galaxy samples in the coming years.</prp:abstract>
